Fun statistic: 

The Probability of completing a goal is:
	•	10% if you have an idea or a goal actually in mind. 
	•	25% if you consciously decide you will do it. 
	•	40% - if you decide when you will do it.
	•	50% - if you plan how you will do it.
	•	65% - if you commit to someone, you will do it. 
	•	95% - if you have a specific accountability appointment with a person you've committed to
*huge jump to 95% when you place structures in place for accountability
**source: The American Society of Training and Development (ASTD)

Just closed on this duplex + a signed option agreement to purchase an additional two duplexes (on one parcel) from the owner over the next year. It’s our first time doing an option and was a way for us to get creative to make the deal work for us. The PP of the duplex was $195k and the agreed upon option PP on the two other duplexes is $320k. Owner wasn’t able to sell the additional two duplexes right now due to being in the middle of a divorce but we weren’t willing to buy the duplex without the other two. The other duplexes make the deal pencil out better so we proposed the option agreement. It’s a 1k option to purchase the two duplexes 180 days from date of divorce and ability to extend another 180 days for an additional 1k. Always learning… always growing the toolbox to make no or “not right now” a yes 💪🏼

We’ve passed plumbing, HVAC, electrical and framing inspections at our flip so now the guys are moving! Drywall up in the main areas and greenboard in the bathroom and should get taped Thursday or Friday :) 

What is greenboard you ask? Greenboard is a special type of drywall that has been treated with a moisture and mold-resistant coating. It’s used in areas with high humidity, such as bathrooms, kitchens, and laundries. Note: it shouldn’t be used in a shower unless you’re putting some other membrane product over it. We are installing an acrylic shower on this one. For all practical purposes, surrounds are waterproof, and the stuff behind it is just there for support. Many do not require any backer at all, and attach directly to the studs or walls or often say can be installed "over any solid surface”.

If bathroom is painted well and has proper ventilation, regular drywall is *generally fine* for outside of the shower but when building new, it only costs about $60 more total for green board, so it’s definitely a nice choice that helps prevent mold growth 🤙🏼

These small, mid and large metros were recently designated the most stable in 2023 🔥 With mortgage rate increases to help fight inflation, some areas have started to experience both a slowdown in home sales as well as a decrease in price. These markets are the most stable according to construction coverage.com and were ranked according to the *chance of a random buyer experiencing at least a 5% price drop*, using data from 2000 to present. For each location, researchers also calculated the largest price drop from 2000 to present, the current median home price, and the percentage change in home price from 2000 to present.

For reference:
* Small metros: 100,000-349,999
* Midsize metros: 350,000-999,999
* Large metros: more than 1,000,000

Find the full article at constructioncoverage.com/research/the-most-stable-housing-markets-2023

Woke up feeling so incredibly grateful. “Everything that I prayed for, became so.” We left our W2 jobs, moved our family across the country and chose to make our side hobby of real estate our full time gig. We get to work with each other and certainly enjoy working for ourselves. Everything we ever dreamed of is coming true so it’s so vital to not be self-limiting with our beliefs ✨

We are officially closed on our flip! 🏡 The new owners are so excited to call this their home and we are 58k richer for it 😉  As a backstory, flipping is a pivot for us. We normally rehab and hold (BRRRR) but rates are high, BRRRR deals are tough to come by, and we definitely don’t want our money to sit around without going to work and making more for us. We prefer fertile money that has lots of babies 😂 We were in and out in 67 days total on this one ($ breakdown below ⬇️)

PP: 245k (242k + closing costs)
Rehab/holding costs: 22k
All in: 267k

Under contract for 339k - commission/closing costs = 325.8 net (I was the selling agent at a 2% listing commission) 
325.8k - 267k= 58.8k profit💰 

We love being our own bosses and getting to work with each other… and we are so grateful for what real estate has done for our family.  In fact, we just booked a family vacay to the Bahamas 👏🏼
So amazing 🥲❤️

First, I want to thank everyone for reaching out and checking on us. We are good 🙏🏼 We had our closet cleared out, ready to take shelter since we don’t have a basement, but the tornado stayed far enough away that we didn’t have to. My heart is heavy for those who were affected. So many lives are upended right now with 114 homes completely destroyed and another 857 damaged. I’m truly in awe of the community coming together to help one another. I also have to say, I’m so proud to watch the investor community be so generous with their time and resources. We are working alongside our close friends @devinramos and @shelbykendall (and taking some serious notes) to offer housing to families that were displaced. With 26 doors here (including our own home), only one of our properties sustained damage and it was minimal. With some elbow grease and borrowed furniture from our family and neighbors, we were able to place one family in a rental of ours that was almost market ready. A neighbor of ours stocked the fridge with groceries and her 9 year old daughter even gave the family $15 of her own money with a card.  My heart 🥲. With a second rehab of ours set to wrap by our contractor on Friday, we should be able to help a second family this weekend but until then will be helping however we can. We are alive and well and able to help ❤️
It’s been a crazy, absolutely INCREDIBLE year ✨… and isn’t this song just perfect for all of us?! 🤩
